node.text:
#ArrecifeAlacranes is home to turtles, sharks, corals and hundreds of other species that need protection. Science is the best tool to take care of the wealth of our seas.
.
Over the next two weeks, 10 scientists with different specialties will explore the area with Oceana and our expedition partner @Blancpain1735. They’ll complete environmental DNA analysis and photomosaic modeling, which will be used to create 3D maps of the reefs and enable a census of the species that inhabit them or use the area as part of their migratory routes.
.
Keep an eye on our feeds and stories for updates on this adventure and follow @oceanamexico for live updates (en español).
.
#Blancpain1735 #BlancpainOceanCommitment #BlancpainFiftyFathoms #FiftyFathoms #ArrecifeAlacranes

node.text:
If we protect and restore our oceans from threats like illegal and irresponsible fishing, they can feed ONE BILLION people a healthy seafood meal each day.
.
Wild fish is a healthy source of protein that doesn’t require fresh water or arable land, produces little carbon dioxide, and costs less per pound than beef, chicken, lamb or pork.
.
Sustainable fishery management can help increase the global fish catch by up to 15% from current levels. Oceana campaigns worldwide to win policy victories that protect our oceans and deliver more seafood to the future. #SaveTheOceansFeedTheWorld

node.title: Save the Oceans, Feed the World

node.text:
We must act together to stop destroying the very planet that sustains us. Join @Oceana, @oak_foundation and the hundreds of organizations that have already signed on to #RiseUp4theOcean.
.
We need to RISE UP together to:
- Restore ocean life
- Invest immediately in a net-zero carbon emissions future
- Speed the transition to a circular and sustainable economy
- Empower and support coastal people
- Unite for stronger global ocean governance
- Protect at least 30% of the ocean by 2030
.
Learn more at RISEUPfortheocean.org
.
#SaveOurOcean #Ocean #SDG14 #OceanClimateAction

node.text:
Actor, singer, author and producer @jennaushkowitz knows how important sharks are to our oceans. "Sharks are so vital to the ecosystem. They're at the top of the food chain and regulate the first population. And without them, we'd be in real danger."
.
Fins from up to 73 million sharks end up in the global shark fin trade every year. Shark finning is the practice of cutting off a shark's fin, and then often discarding the shark back into the ocean where it drowns. Sharks need your help.
.
That's why we're working with @knockaround to help protect sharks and our oceans. $5 from every pair of @sharkweek Fort Knocks sunglasses will be donated to Oceana. Get your pair from @knockaround and follow the link in our bio to tell Congress to ban the sale of shark fins in the U.S. #FinBanNow
.

node.text: Coconut octopuses are known to collect coconut shells to hide in. 🥥 But with so much pollution in our oceans, these octopuses sometimes end up grabbing plastic instead. This kind of single-use plastic is flooding our oceans and putting marine life at serious risk. That's why Oceana's proven campaigns focus on addressing the ocean's biggest threats, including plastic pollution, to protect and restore the world's oceans. #WorldCoconutDay

Dangerous mile-long drift gillnets can entangle and kill sperm whales, leatherback sea turtles, and other ocean animals. But legislation introduced in Congress would change this and ensure these “walls of death” are eliminated from all U.S. waters for good. Add your name to help get these deadly drift gillnets out of the water and save whales today. Link in bio.

More than half of the world’s marine species will be threatened with extinction by 2100 if no significant changes are made. This loss of species is not only heartbreaking, but it also reduces the ocean’s ability to provide food, maintain water quality, and recover from other threats. Our oceans need us NOW. That's why Oceana works to increase marine biodiversity, restore ocean abundance, safeguard habitat, and protect our oceans for generations to come. 🌊
